Claims WHAT IS CLAIMED IS: 1. An applicator for applying an on-skin assembly to skin of a host, the applicator comprising: an insertion assembly configured to insert at least a portion of the on-skin assembly into the skin of the host; a housing configured to receive the insertion assembly, the housing comprising an aperture through which the on-skin assembly is configured to pass; an actuation member configured to, upon activation, actuate the insertion assembly to insert at least the portion of the on-skin assembly into the skin of the host; and a sealing element configured to provide a sterile barrier and a vapor barrier between an internal environment of the housing and an external environment of the housing. 2. The applicator of Claim 1, wherein the sealing element is releasable from the applicator. 3. The applicator of Claim 1 , further comprising the on-skin assembly. 4. The applicator of Claim 3, wherein the on-skin assembly comprises a sensor. 5. The applicator of Claim 3, wherein the on-skin assembly comprises a transmitter. 6. The applicator of Claim 3, wherein the on-skin assembly comprises an adhesive layer configured to adhere the on-skin assembly to the skin of the host. 7. The applicator of Claim 1, further comprising a support member configured to inhibit at least lateral movement of the insertion assembly. 8. The applicator of Claim 7, wherein the support member comprises an elastomeric membrane. 9. The applicator of Claim 1, wherein the insertion assembly comprises a needle. 10. The applicator of Claim 1, further comprising one or more ridges or recesses configured to provide a tactile indication of grip for the host. 11. The applicator of Claim 1, wherein the applicator has a cross-sectional shape configured to provide a tactile indication of grip for the host. 12. The applicator of Claim 1, further comprising at least one protrusion configured to inhibit rolling of the applicator. 13. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, wherein the housing comprises a vent configured to be permeable to a sterilizing gas. 14. The applicator of Claim 13, wherein the sealing element is configured to seal the vent. 15. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, wherein the sealing element is configured to seal both the aperture and the actuation member. 16. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, wherein the actuation member comprises a material that is permeable to a sterilizing gas. 17. The applicator of Claim 1, wherein the sealing element comprises at least one of a metallic foil, a metallic substrate, an aluminum oxide coated polymer, parylene, a polymer coated with a metal applied via vapor metallization, a silicon dioxide coated polymer, or any material having a moisture vapor transmission rate less than 10 grams/1 OOin 2 or preferably less than 1 grams/ 1 OOin 2 . 18. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, wherein the sealing element comprises a removable cap configured to couple with a portion of the housing. 19. The applicator of Claim 18, wherein the removable cap is configured to couple with a proximal portion of the housing. 20. The applicator of Claim 18, wherein the removable cap is configured to couple with a distal portion of the housing. 21. The applicator of Claim 18, wherein the removable cap is configured to couple with the housing in a single axial orientation. 22. The applicator of Claim 18, wherein the removable cap is configured to couple with the portion of the housing via threads. 23. The applicator of Claim 18, wherein the removable cap is configured to couple with the portion of the housing via a frangible member. 24. The applicator of Claim 23, wherein the frangible member is configured to provide a tamper indication when broken. 25. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, further comprising a tamper indicator. 26. The applicator of Claim 18, wherein the sealing element further comprises an o- ring configured to provide a seal between the removable cap and the housing. 27. The applicator of Claim 18, wherein the removable cap covers the actuation member. 28. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, wherein the sealing element comprises a first layer being permeable to a sterilizing gas and a second layer being substantially impermeable to water vapor. 29. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, wherein the sealing element comprises a first layer being substantially impermeable to water vapor and sealing the aperture. 30. The applicator of Claim 29, wherein the sealing element further comprises a second layer being substantially impermeable to water vapor and sealing the actuation member. 31. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, wherein the sealing element comprises a peelable layer coupled to at least a portion of the housing. 32. The applicator of Claim 31, wherein the peelable layer is configured to provide a tamper indication when removed. 33. The applicator of Claim 31, wherein the peelable layer is configured to seal a distal opening of the housing. 34. The applicator of Claim 33, wherein the peelable layer is configured to further seal the actuation member. 35. The applicator of any of Claims 31-34, wherein the peelable layer is configured to seal a vent configured to be permeable to a sterilizing gas. 36. The applicator of Claim 35, wherein the vent is disposed on a side of the housing. 37. The applicator of Claim 35, wherein the vent is disposed on a distal surface of the housing. 38. The applicator of Claim 35, wherein a porous polymeric component is inserted into the vent. 39. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, wherein the sealing element comprises a flexible member disposed over at least a portion of the housing. 40. The applicator of Claim 39, wherein the flexible member comprises an elastomer. 41. The applicator of Claim 39, wherein the flexible member covers the actuation member. 42. The applicator of Claim 39, wherein the flexible member is operatively coupled to the actuation member. 43. The applicator of Claim 39, wherein the flexible member has a bistable configuration so as to provide a visual indication of deployment after activation. 44. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, wherein the sealing element comprises a frangible member. 45. The applicator of Claim 44, wherein the frangible member covers the actuation member, and wherein removal of the frangible member exposes the actuation member for activation. 46. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, wherein the sealing element comprises a cup having a removable lid. 47. The applicator of Claim 46, wherein the cup is configured to be collapsible after removal of the lid. 48. The applicator of Claim 46, wherein the cup is configured to seal applicator from an environment outside the cup. 49. The applicator of Claim 46, wherein the cup comprises an on-skin assembly alignment feature. 50. The applicator of Claim 46, wherein the cup comprises a needle protection feature. 51. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, wherein the sealing element comprises a plug configured to couple to the housing via a friction fit. 52. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, wherein the actuation member is disposed on a side of the housing. 53. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, wherein the actuation member is disposed on a proximal portion of the housing. 54. The applicator of Claim 53, wherein the actuation member is recessed into the proximal portion of the housing. 55. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, wherein the actuation member comprises a cap coupled to a proximal portion of the housing. 56. The applicator of Claim 55, wherein the actuation member is configured to be activated by moving the cap in a distal direction. 57. The applicator of Claim 55, wherein the sealing element further comprises a sealing layer disposed between the cap and the housing. 58. The applicator of Claim 57, wherein the cap comprises a protrusion configured to pierce the sealing layer and thereby activate the insertion assembly. 59. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, wherein the insertion assembly is driven by a spring force. 60. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, wherein the needle is retracted from the insertion assembly after the insertion assembly inserts the on-skin assembly. 61. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, further comprising a safety member configured to prevent activation of the actuation member. 62. The applicator of Claim 61, wherein the safety member comprises a frangible member, the frangible member being configured to prevent activation of the actuation member, at least until the frangible member is broken. 63. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, wherein the sealing element comprises a first portion comprising at least one perforation and an adhesive layer disposed on a first side of the first portion. 64. The applicator of Claim 63, wherein the sealing element further comprises a second portion disposed adjacent to the first side of the first portion, the second portion configurable in a first configuration wherein the first portion is spatially separated from the second portion and a second configuration wherein the second portion is adhered to the first portion via the adhesive layer, wherein: the sealing element is permeable to a sterilizing gas in the first configuration; and the sealing element is impermeable to the sterilizing gas in the second configuration. 65. The applicator of Claim 64, wherein the second portion is configured to transition from the first configuration to the second configuration when the applicator is subjected to at least a partial vacuum exceeding a threshold. 66. The applicator of any of Claims 1-12, wherein the housing is disposable. 67. A method of manufacturing an applicator configured to apply an on-skin assembly to skin of a host, the method comprising: providing an insertion assembly configured to insert at least a portion of the on- skin assembly into the skin of the host; 

 providing a housing configured to receive the insertion assembly, the housing comprising an aperture through which the on-skin assembly is configured to pass; providing an actuation member configured to, upon activation, actuate the insertion assembly to insert at least the portion of the on-skin assembly into the skin of the host; and providing a sealing element configured to provide a sterile barrier and a vapor barrier between an internal environment of the housing and an external environment of the housing. 68. A method of manufacturing an applicator configured to apply an on-skin assembly to skin of a host, the method comprising: providing an insertion assembly configured to insert at least a portion of the on- skin assembly into the skin of the host; providing a housing configured to receive the insertion assembly, the housing comprising an aperture through which the on-skin assembly is configured to pass; providing an actuation member configured to, upon activation, actuate the insertion assembly to insert at least the portion of the on-skin assembly into the skin of the host; exposing at least an internal environment of the housing to a sterilizing gas; allowing for egress of the sterilizing gas from the internal environment of the housing; and sealing the internal environment of the housing from an external environment of the housing. 69. The method of Claim 68, wherein at least sealing the internal environment of the housing from an external environment of the housing is performed simultaneously for a plurality of applicators. 70. The method of Claim 69, wherein sealing the internal environment of the housing from an external environment of the housing comprises subjecting the plurality of applicators to a partial vacuum exceeding a threshold such that a sealing element of each of the plurality of applicators transitions from being permeable to the sterilizing gas to being impermeable to the sterilizing gas. 71. The method of Claim 69, wherein sealing the internal environment of the housing from an external environment of the housing comprises subjecting the plurality of applicators to a physical force sufficient to cause a sealing element of each of the plurality of applicators to transition from a first physical configuration permeable to the sterilizing gas to a second physical configuration impermeable to the sterilizing gas. 72. The method of Claim 69, wherein sealing the internal environment of the housing from an external environment of the housing comprises subjecting a sealing element, comprising a plurality of perforations, of each the plurality of applicators to a temperature sufficient to at least partially melt each of the sealing elements thereby sealing the plurality of perforations in each of the sealing elements. 73. The method of Claim 69, wherein sealing the internal environment of the housing from an external environment of the housing comprises subjecting a sealing element, comprising a porous polymeric component, of each of the plurality of applicators to a temperature sufficient to form a sintered layer in the porous polymeric component of each sealing element. 74. The method of Claim 69, wherein sealing the internal environment of the housing from an external environment of the housing comprises depositing a layer impermeable to the sterilizing gas on at least a portion of each of the plurality of applicators. 75. The method of Claim 74, wherein the sealing element comprises at least one of a metallic foil, a metallic substrate, an aluminum oxide coated polymer, parylene, a polymer coated with a metal applied via vapor metallization, a silicon dioxide coated polymer, or any material having a moisture vapor transmission rate less than 10 grams/1 OOin 2 or preferably less than 1 grams/ 1 OOin 2 . 76. An applicator for applying an on-skin assembly to skin of a host, the applicator comprising: an insertion assembly configured to insert at least a portion of the on-skin assembly into the skin of the host; a housing configured to receive the insertion assembly, the housing comprising an aperture through which the on-skin assembly is configured to pass; an actuation member configured to, upon activation, actuate the insertion assembly to insert at least the portion of the on-skin assembly into the skin of the host; and 

 a removable cap configured to couple with a portion of the housing; and a layer comprising a gas permeable material, the sealing element configured to allow for ingress and egress of a sterilizing gas. 77. The applicator of Claim 76, wherein the removable cap includes an aperture located at a bottom end of the removable cap. 78. The applicator of Claim 77, wherein the layer is coupled to the bottom of the removable cap and encloses the aperture. 79. The applicator of Claim 77, wherein the removable cap includes a raised platform from the bottom end of the removable cap. 80. The applicator of Claim 79, wherein the raised platform is spaced a predetermined distance from the on- skin assembly. 81. The applicator of Claim 80, wherein the raised platform includes a plurality of channels. 82. The applicator of Claim 81, wherein the plurality of channels are spaced equidistantly along the circumference of the raised platform. 83. The applicator of Claim 81, wherein the plurality of channels are configured to allow for ingress of the sterilizing gas into the housing and egress of the sterilizing gas out of the housing. 84. The applicator of any of Claims 76-83, further comprising a safety feature to prevent actuation of the actuation member. 85. The applicator of Claim 84, wherein the safety feature is unlocked by pressing the housing in a distal direction. 86. The applicator of Claim 85, wherein the pressing of the housing in a distal direction actuates the housing along an inner housing of the applicator. 87. The applicator of Claim 86, wherein the actuation member is aligned with a trigger arm, the actuation member configured to laterally actuate and deflect the trigger arm. 88. The applicator of any of Claims 76-87, wherein the removable cap is configured to couple with a proximal portion of the housing. 89. The applicator of any of Claims 76-87, wherein the removable cap is configured to couple with a distal portion of the housing.
